**Reading.** The curve survives small thresholds easily (every OEM touches many
states), then collapses near the share scale of state market leaders. A rising
τ_c over years would mean national connectivity increasingly depends on
dominant positions; a falling one, that mid-size OEMs are knitting the market.

## Fuel regime calendar

::: {#a776fc57 .cell execution_count=4}
``` {.python .cell-code}
panel_year = con.execute("SELECT * FROM panel_state_year WHERE state_code <> 'ALL'").df()
regimes = tr.classify_regimes(panel_year[panel_year["year"] <= latest])

order = (regimes[regimes["year"] == latest].sort_values("regime")["state_code"]).tolist()
cal = regimes.pivot_table(index="state_code", columns="year", values="regime", aggfunc="first")
cal = cal.reindex(order)
code = {"fossil_dominant": 0, "multi_fuel": 1, "cng_transitioned": 2, "ev_emerging": 3}
z = cal.replace(code)

fig = go.Figure(go.Heatmap(
    z=z.values, x=cal.columns, y=cal.index,
    colorscale=[[0, "#B8B8B8"], [0.33, "#86BBD8"], [0.66, "#758E4F"], [1.0, "#E4572E"]],
    colorbar=dict(tickvals=[0, 1, 2, 3],
                  ticktext=["fossil", "multi-fuel", "CNG", "EV-emerging"]),
))
fig.update_layout(title="Regime calendar — every state's energy-transition path",
                  height=700, xaxis_title="year")
fig.show()
```

