## Finding

The percolation curve shows the OEM–state network is **robust to weak-link
removal and collapses only near the market-leader share scale (τ_c ≈ 40%+)** —
national market cohesion rides on a few dominant footholds, not on the long
tail of small presences. The regime analysis shows **fossil-dominant and
CNG-transitioned states are near-absorbing** (once there, states stay), while
**EV-emerging is not yet absorbing** — states near the 5% EV line can slip
back, i.e. the EV transition had not yet ratcheted as of the latest full year.
The CNG stepping-stone path (fossil → CNG → EV) is visible in the calendar for
the gas-grid states (GJ, MH, DL/NCR), while several southern states jump
directly toward EV-emerging.

**Publishable angle**: regime ratchet asymmetry (CNG absorbs, EV doesn't yet)
+ τ_c evolution as a market-cohesion observable. Upgrade path: HMM-fitted
regimes (hmmlearn) and bootstrap CIs on τ_c — see `docs/roadmap`.
